In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims July 28, 2012, as World Hepatitis Day. He highlights the global prevalence of viral hepatitis and its impact on the health of millions of people, including Americans. Hepatitis B and C are specifically mentioned as leading causes of liver cancer and chronic infections. The article emphasizes the importance of awareness, prevention, and control of hepatitis through vaccines, early detection, and treatment. The burden of the disease is highlighted, particularly among African American, Hispanic, Asian American and Pacific Islander communities, and those born between 1945 and 1965. The article also mentions various initiatives, programs, and partnerships aimed at addressing viral hepatitis, including the Healthy People 2020 initiative and the Affordable Care Act. The proclamation calls for increased awareness and support for those affected by hepatitis and encourages participation in activities that promote prevention.